<promed@promedmail.org>

[The article referenced in the media report above is:
Dan JM, Mateus J, Kato Y, et al. Immunological memory to SARS-CoV-2 assessed for greater than six months after infection. bioRxiv 2020.11.15.383323; doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.11.15.383323
------------------------------------------------------------------
"Abstract
---------
"Understanding immune memory to SARS-CoV-2 is critical for improving diagnostics and vaccines, and for assessing the likely future course of the pandemic. We analyzed multiple compartments of circulating immune memory to SARS-CoV-2 in 185 COVID-19 cases, including 41 cases at longer than 6 months post-infection. Spike IgG was relatively stable over 6+ months. Spike-specific memory B cells were more abundant at 6 months than at 1 month. SARS-CoV-2-specific CD4+ T cells and CD8+ T cells declined with a half-life of 3-5 months. By studying antibody, memory B cell, CD4+ T cell, and CD8+ T cell memory to SARS-CoV-2 in an integrated manner, we observed that each component of SARS-CoV-2 immune memory exhibited distinct kinetics."

Subjects for the study while covering asymptomatic, mild, moderate, and severe COVID-19 cases, the majority (92%) were mild and not requiring hospitalization, although 97% did report symptomatic disease. As waning immunity has been observed to occur more in milder clinical expression, the findings of the study are more intriguing, highlighting that there is persistent immunity up through 5-6+ months following infection. The subjects included 43% male and 57% females. Age distributions were not given. Race distribution included 77% white, 3% African American, 8% Asian. Ethnicity included 15% Hispanic.

The authors noted that spike IgG titers lasted 6-8 months following symptom onset, and receptor binding domain IgG and SARS-CoV-2 pseudovirus neutralizing antibody titers were similarly stable. At 5 months or more after the onset of symptoms, almost all subjects were positive for SARS-CoV-2 spike and receptor binding domain IgG.

The authors noted that memory B cells specific for the spike or receptor binding domain were detected in almost all individuals with COVID-19, with no half life noted 5+ months following infection. The authors pointed out that B cell memory to other infections is long lived -- 60+ years following smallpox vaccination and 90+ years after infection with influenza. In addition, memory T cell half-lives observed over a 6+ month period following symptom onsets were similar to those observed following yellow fever vaccination. The authors noted that these findings suggest that T cell memory "might reach a more stable plateau, or slower decay phase, later than the 1st 6 months post-infection". They concluded that a "hypothesis that SARS-CoV-2 memory T cells and B cells would be capable of substantially limiting SARS-CoV-2 dissemination and/or cumulative viral load, resulting in substantially reduced COVID-19 disease severity." With an observation that "immune memory consisting of at least 3 immunological compartments was measurable in about 90% of subjects more than 5 months following onset of symptoms, indicating that durable immunity against secondary COVID-19 disease is a possibility in most individuals."

Remember, we have only had almost 11 months experience with this virus. If these findings are reproducible and show an even longer duration of immunity, this is promising for duration of immunity following vaccination, as well as protection against 2nd infections ("reinfection"). - Mod.MPP]

