[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 218. A note of caution re weekend reporting artifact. During the weekend period, some countries do not submit reports to WHO (or elsewhere) or some reporting units within countries do not submit reports so it appears as though transmission may be slowing down when it is reporting that is slowing down.

Data by country, area, or territory for 17 Nov 2020 can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/WHO%20daily%20tablesNov17_1605642771.pdf.

- The Americas region reported 39.7% of daily case numbers and 23.9% of the daily deaths reported in the past 24 hours, maintaining its position as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 23.3 million cases.

- The European region reported 42.8 of daily case numbers and 53.0% of the daily deaths reported in the past 24 hours, and total cumulative cases reported exceed 15.4 million. Countries not reporting cases today (17 Nov 2020) include Spain, Israel, Sweden, and Kazakhstan, among others.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 7.2% of daily case numbers and 12.0% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 3.61 million cases.

- The African region reported 1.0% of daily case numbers and 1.9% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours and has reported more than 1.40 million cases. Countries not reporting any new cases include Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Senegal, DR Congo, Gabon, and Botswana among others.

- The Western Pacific region reported 1.0% of daily case numbers and 0.52% of the deaths reported in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of 0.80 million cases. Viet Nam reported 2 cases and Mongolia 3 cases.

- The South East Asia region reported 8.3% of the daily newly reported cases and 8.6% of reported deaths in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 10.0 million cases. Thailand has reported 3 cases, Bhutan 2 cases.

Impression: There is a continued dominance of Europe and the Americas region.

On the Overview tab at the WHO source URL, the epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 17 Nov 2020, is an excellent visual representation of the pandemic. - Mod.MPP]

